<a href="https://pubads.g.doubleclick.net/gampad/jump?iu=0&sz=1&c=234" target="_blank"><img src="https://pubads.g.doubleclick.net/gampad/ad?iu=0&sz=1&c=234" border="0" alt=""></a>“My family and I are very happy. Our mkhukhu was too small for all of us, but the Wendy House is very nice. “Thanks to everyone who contributed,” she said.Olivia made headlines on 5 February when she was beaten in the streets of Joburg by an ANC member. The incident angered many people around the country. But now Olivia can smile again after receiving the house. Dianne Bayley from Bryanston, north of Joburg, the woman behind the initiative, said she was saddened by the disturbing footage and made it her mission to find Olivia and restore some faith in humanity.“I saw the video footage on Twitter and was appalled that a huge man could beat an older woman while other men and policemen looked on.” Dianne came across the photo of Olivia standing in front of her shack and was inspired to set up a BackaBuddy crowdfunding campaign.Zane Groenewald of BackaBuddysaid they were also touched by Olivia’s story. “The kindness Olivia experienced after her ordeal shows our ability as South Africans to positively impact those around us.”